<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Pilgrimages">Pilgrimages</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Jainism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=26" title="Edit section: Pilgrimages">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tirtha_(Jainism)" title="Tirtha (Jainism)">Tirtha (Jainism)</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Shikharji_Parasnath_Giridih.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Shikharji_Parasnath_Giridih.jpg/170px-Shikharji_Parasnath_Giridih.jpg" decoding="async" width="170" height="128" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Shikharji_Parasnath_Giridih.jpg/255px-Shikharji_Parasnath_Giridih.jpg 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Shikharji_Parasnath_Giridih.jpg/340px-Shikharji_Parasnath_Giridih.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2816" data-file-height="2112" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Shikharji_Parasnath_Giridih.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shikharji" title="Shikharji">Shikharji</a></div></div></div>
<p>Jain <i>Tirtha</i> (pilgrim) sites are divided into the following categories:<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTETitze1998_295-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTETitze1998-295">&#91;285&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li><i>Siddhakshetra</i>&#160;&#8211;&#160;Site believed to be of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moksha_(Jainism)" title="Moksha (Jainism)"><i>moksha</i></a> of an <i>arihant</i> (<i>kevalin</i>) or <i>tirthankara</i>, such as: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Kailash" title="Mount Kailash">Ashtapada</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shikharji" title="Shikharji">Shikharji</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Girnar" title="Girnar">Girnar</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pawapuri" title="Pawapuri">Pawapuri</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palitana" title="Palitana">Palitana</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mangi-Tungi" title="Mangi-Tungi">Mangi-Tungi</a>, and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Champapuri" title="Champapuri">Champapuri</a> (capital of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anga" title="Anga">Anga</a>).</li>
<li><i>Atishayakshetra</i>&#160;&#8211;&#160;Locations where divine events are believed to have occurred, such as: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahavirji" class="mw-redirect" title="Mahavirji">Mahavirji</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rishabhdeo" title="Rishabhdeo">Rishabhdeo</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kundalpur" title="Kundalpur">Kundalpur</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tijara_Jain_Temple" class="mw-redirect" title="Tijara Jain Temple">Tijara</a>, and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aharji" title="Aharji">Aharji</a>.</li>
<li><i>Puranakshetra</i>&#160;&#8211;&#160; Places associated with the lives of great men, such as: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ayodhya" title="Ayodhya">Ayodhya</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vidisha" title="Vidisha">Vidisha</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hastinapur" title="Hastinapur">Hastinapur</a>, and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rajgir" title="Rajgir">Rajgir</a>.</li>
<li><i>Gyanakshetra</i>&#160;&#8211;&#160; Places associated with famous <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acharya" title="Acharya">acharyas</a></i>, or centers of learning, such as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shravanabelagola" title="Shravanabelagola">Shravanabelagola</a>.</li></ul>
<p>Outside contemporary India, Jain communities built <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nagarparkar_Jain_Temples" title="Nagarparkar Jain Temples">temples</a> in locations such as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nagarparkar" title="Nagarparkar">Nagarparkar</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sindh" title="Sindh">Sindh</a> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pakistan" title="Pakistan">Pakistan</a>). However, according to a UNESCO tentative world heritage site application, Nagarparkar was not a "major religious centre or a place of pilgrimage" for Jainism, but it was once an important cultural landscape before "the last remaining Jain community left the area in 1947 at Partition".<sup id="cite_ref-296" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-296">&#91;286&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Statues_and_sculptures">Statues and sculptures</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Jainism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=27" title="Edit section: Statues and sculptures">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jain_sculpture" title="Jain sculpture">Jain sculpture</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Thirthankara_Suparshvanath_Museum_Rietberg_RVI_306.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Thirthankara_Suparshvanath_Museum_Rietberg_RVI_306.jpg/170px-Thirthankara_Suparshvanath_Museum_Rietberg_RVI_306.jpg" decoding="async" width="170" height="190" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Thirthankara_Suparshvanath_Museum_Rietberg_RVI_306.jpg/255px-Thirthankara_Suparshvanath_Museum_Rietberg_RVI_306.jpg 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Thirthankara_Suparshvanath_Museum_Rietberg_RVI_306.jpg/340px-Thirthankara_Suparshvanath_Museum_Rietberg_RVI_306.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2152" data-file-height="2403" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Thirthankara_Suparshvanath_Museum_Rietberg_RVI_306.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Idol of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supar%C5%9Bvan%C4%81tha" class="mw-redirect" title="Suparśvanātha">Suparśvanātha</a></div></div></div>
<p>Jain sculptures usually depict one of the twenty-four <i>tīrthaṅkaras</i>; Parshvanatha, Rishabhanatha and Mahāvīra are among the more popular, often seated in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lotus_position" title="Lotus position">lotus position</a> or <i>kayotsarga</i>, along with <i>Arihant</i>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bahubali" title="Bahubali">Bahubali</a>, and protector deities like <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ambika_(Jainism)" title="Ambika (Jainism)">Ambika</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEArora2007405_297-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEArora2007405-297">&#91;287&#93;</a></sup> Quadruple images are also popular. <i>Tirthankar</i> idols look similar, differentiated by their individual symbol, except for Parshvanatha whose head is crowned by a snake. Digambara images are naked without any beautification, whereas Śvētāmbara depictions are clothed and ornamented.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTECort2010184_298-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTECort2010184-298">&#91;288&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>A monolithic, 18-metre (59-foot) statue of Bahubali, <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gommateshvara" class="mw-redirect" title="Gommateshvara">Gommateshvara</a></i>, built in 981 CE by the Ganga minister and commander <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chavundaraya" title="Chavundaraya">Chavundaraya</a>, is situated on a hilltop in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shravanabelagola" title="Shravanabelagola">Shravanabelagola</a> in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karnataka" title="Karnataka">Karnataka</a>. This statue was voted first in the SMS poll Seven Wonders of India conducted by <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Times_of_India" title="The Times of India">The Times of India</a></i>.<sup id="cite_ref-299" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-299">&#91;289&#93;</a></sup> The 33&#160;m (108&#160;ft) tall <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statue_of_Ahi%E1%B9%83s%C4%81" class="mw-redirect" title="Statue of Ahiṃsā">Statue of Ahiṃsā</a> (depicting Rishabhanatha) was erected in the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nashik_district" title="Nashik district">Nashik district</a> in 2015.<sup id="cite_ref-300" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-300">&#91;290&#93;</a></sup> Idols are often made in <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ashtadhatu" title="Ashtadhatu">Ashtadhatu</a></i> (literally "eight metals"), namely <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akota_Bronze" class="mw-redirect" title="Akota Bronze">Akota Bronze</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brass" title="Brass">brass</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gold" title="Gold">gold</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silver" title="Silver">silver</a>, stone <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monolith" title="Monolith">monoliths</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rock_cut" class="mw-redirect" title="Rock cut">rock cut</a>, and precious stones.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPratapaditya_Pal198622_301-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPratapaditya_Pal198622-301">&#91;291&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-302" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-302">&#91;292&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Symbols">Symbols</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Jainism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=28" title="Edit section: Symbols">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jain_symbols" title="Jain symbols">Jain symbols</a></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r923042769/mw-parser-output/.tmulti"/><div class="thumb tmulti tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:267px;max-width:267px"><div class="trow"><div class="tsingle" style="width:92px;max-width:92px"><div class="thumbimage"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Om_ja%C3%AFn_orange.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Om_ja%C3%AFn_orange.svg/90px-Om_ja%C3%AFn_orange.svg.png" decoding="async" width="90" height="112" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Om_ja%C3%AFn_orange.svg/135px-Om_ja%C3%AFn_orange.svg.png 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Om_ja%C3%AFn_orange.svg/180px-Om_ja%C3%AFn_orange.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="167" data-file-height="208" /></a></div><div class="thumbcaption"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Om#Jainism" title="Om">Om in Jainism</a></div></div><div class="tsingle" style="width:171px;max-width:171px"><div class="thumbimage"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Jain_flag.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Jain_flag.jpg/169px-Jain_flag.jpg" decoding="async" width="169" height="113" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Jain_flag.jpg/254px-Jain_flag.jpg 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Jain_flag.jpg/338px-Jain_flag.jpg 2x" data-file-width="688" data-file-height="460" /></a></div><div class="thumbcaption"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jain_Flag" class="mw-redirect" title="Jain Flag">Jain Flag</a></div></div></div></div></div>
<p>Jain icons and arts incorporate symbols such as the swastika, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Om#Jainism" title="Om"><i>Om</i></a>, and the <i>Ashtamangala</i>. In Jainism, <i>Om</i> is a condensed reference to the initials "A-A-A-U-M" of the five parameshthis: "<i>Arihant</i>, <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ashiri" class="mw-redirect" title="Ashiri">Ashiri</a></i>, <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acharya" title="Acharya">Acharya</a></i>, <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Upajjhaya" class="mw-redirect" title="Upajjhaya">Upajjhaya</a></i>, <i>Muni</i>",<sup id="cite_ref-303" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-303">&#91;293&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp1925410–411_304-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp1925410–411-304">&#91;294&#93;</a></sup> or the five lines of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Namokara_Mantra" class="mw-redirect" title="Namokara Mantra"><i>Ṇamōkāra</i> Mantra</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAgarwal2012135_305-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAgarwal2012135-305">&#91;295&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAgarwal201380_306-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAgarwal201380-306">&#91;296&#93;</a></sup> The <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ashtamangala" title="Ashtamangala">Ashtamangala</a></i> is a set of eight auspicious symbols:<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTETitze1998234_307-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTETitze1998234-307">&#91;297&#93;</a></sup> in the Digambara tradition, these are <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chatra_(umbrella)" title="Chatra (umbrella)">Chatra</a>, <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dhvaja" title="Dhvaja">Dhvaja</a></i>, <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalasha" title="Kalasha">Kalasha</a></i>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fly-whisk" title="Fly-whisk">Fly-whisk</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mirror" title="Mirror">Mirror</a>, Chair, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hand_fan" title="Hand fan">Hand fan</a> and Vessel. In the Śvētāmbar tradition, they are Swastika, <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Srivatsa" class="mw-redirect" title="Srivatsa">Srivatsa</a></i>, <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nandavarta" title="Nandavarta">Nandavarta</a></i>, <i>Vardhmanaka</i> (food vessel), <i>Bhadrasana</i> (seat), <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalasha" title="Kalasha">Kalasha</a></i> (pot), <i>Darpan</i> (mirror) and pair of fish.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTETitze1998234_307-1" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTETitze1998234-307">&#91;297&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The hand with a wheel on the palm symbolizes <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ahimsa_in_Jainism" title="Ahimsa in Jainism"><i>ahimsā</i></a>. The wheel represents the <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dharmachakra" title="Dharmachakra">dharmachakra</a></i>, which stands for the resolve to halt the <i>saṃsāra</i> (wandering) through the relentless pursuit of <i>ahimsā</i>. The five colours of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jain_flag" title="Jain flag">Jain flag</a> represent the <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pa%C3%B1ca-Parame%E1%B9%A3%E1%B9%ADhi" title="Pañca-Parameṣṭhi">Pañca-Parameṣṭhi</a></i> and the five vows.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVijay_K._Jain2012iv_308-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVijay_K._Jain2012iv-308">&#91;298&#93;</a></sup> The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swastika" title="Swastika">swastika</a>'s four arms symbolise the four realms in which rebirth occurs according to Jainism: humans, heavenly beings, hellish beings and non-humans.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTECort2001a17_309-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTECort2001a17-309">&#91;299&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEJansmaJain2006123_310-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJansmaJain2006123-310">&#91;300&#93;</a></sup> The three dots on the top represent the three jewels mentioned in ancient texts: correct faith, correct understanding and correct conduct, believed to lead to spiritual perfection.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTECort2001a17–18_311-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTECort2001a17–18-311">&#91;301&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 1974, on the 2500th anniversary of the nirvana of Mahāvīra, the Jain community chose a single combined image for Jainism.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERobinson2006225_312-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTERobinson2006225-312">&#91;302&#93;</a></sup> It depicts the three <i>lokas</i>, heaven, the human world and hell. The semi-circular topmost portion symbolizes <i>Siddhashila</i>, a zone beyond the three realms. The Jain swastika and the symbol of <i>Ahiṃsā</i> are included, with the Jain mantra <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parasparopagraho_Jivanam" title="Parasparopagraho Jivanam">Parasparopagraho Jīvānām</a></i><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESangave2001123_313-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTESangave2001123-313">&#91;303&#93;</a></sup> from sūtra 5.21 of Umaswati's <i>Tattvarthasūtra</i>, meaning "souls render service to one another".<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVallely2013358_314-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVallely2013358-314">&#91;304&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Jainism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=29" title="Edit section: History">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Jainism" title="History of Jainism">History of Jainism</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Photo_of_lord_adinath_bhagwan_at_kundalpur.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Photo_of_lord_adinath_bhagwan_at_kundalpur.JPG/170px-Photo_of_lord_adinath_bhagwan_at_kundalpur.JPG" decoding="async" width="170" height="128" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Photo_of_lord_adinath_bhagwan_at_kundalpur.JPG/255px-Photo_of_lord_adinath_bhagwan_at_kundalpur.JPG 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Photo_of_lord_adinath_bhagwan_at_kundalpur.JPG/340px-Photo_of_lord_adinath_bhagwan_at_kundalpur.JPG 2x" data-file-width="4320" data-file-height="3240" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Photo_of_lord_adinath_bhagwan_at_kundalpur.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rishabhanatha" title="Rishabhanatha">Rishabhdev</a>, believed to have lived over a 10<sup>1631</sup> years ago, is considered the traditional founder of Jainism.</div></div></div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Ancient">Ancient</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Jainism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=30" title="Edit section: Ancient">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timeline_of_Jainism" title="Timeline of Jainism">Timeline of Jainism</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C5%9Arama%E1%B9%87a" title="Śramaṇa">Śramaṇa</a></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r923042769/mw-parser-output/.tmulti"/><div class="thumb tmulti tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:331px;max-width:331px"><div class="trow"><div class="tsingle" style="width:159px;max-width:159px"><div class="thumbimage"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Ashoka_Pillar_at_Feroze_Shah_Kotla,_Delhi_03.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/Ashoka_Pillar_at_Feroze_Shah_Kotla%2C_Delhi_03.JPG/157px-Ashoka_Pillar_at_Feroze_Shah_Kotla%2C_Delhi_03.JPG" decoding="async" width="157" height="209" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/Ashoka_Pillar_at_Feroze_Shah_Kotla%2C_Delhi_03.JPG/236px-Ashoka_Pillar_at_Feroze_Shah_Kotla%2C_Delhi_03.JPG 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/Ashoka_Pillar_at_Feroze_Shah_Kotla%2C_Delhi_03.JPG/314px-Ashoka_Pillar_at_Feroze_Shah_Kotla%2C_Delhi_03.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2304" data-file-height="3072" /></a></div><div class="thumbcaption">Jain inscription of Ashoka (c.236 BCE)</div></div><div class="tsingle" style="width:168px;max-width:168px"><div class="thumbimage"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Shrine_with_Four_Jinas_(Rishabhanatha_(Adinatha)),_Parshvanatha,_Neminatha,_and_Mahavira)_LACMA_M.85.55_(1_of_4).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/Shrine_with_Four_Jinas_%28Rishabhanatha_%28Adinatha%29%29%2C_Parshvanatha%2C_Neminatha%2C_and_Mahavira%29_LACMA_M.85.55_%281_of_4%29.jpg/166px-Shrine_with_Four_Jinas_%28Rishabhanatha_%28Adinatha%29%29%2C_Parshvanatha%2C_Neminatha%2C_and_Mahavira%29_LACMA_M.85.55_%281_of_4%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="166" height="207" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/Shrine_with_Four_Jinas_%28Rishabhanatha_%28Adinatha%29%29%2C_Parshvanatha%2C_Neminatha%2C_and_Mahavira%29_LACMA_M.85.55_%281_of_4%29.jpg/249px-Shrine_with_Four_Jinas_%28Rishabhanatha_%28Adinatha%29%29%2C_Parshvanatha%2C_Neminatha%2C_and_Mahavira%29_LACMA_M.85.55_%281_of_4%29.jpg 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/Shrine_with_Four_Jinas_%28Rishabhanatha_%28Adinatha%29%29%2C_Parshvanatha%2C_Neminatha%2C_and_Mahavira%29_LACMA_M.85.55_%281_of_4%29.jpg/332px-Shrine_with_Four_Jinas_%28Rishabhanatha_%28Adinatha%29%29%2C_Parshvanatha%2C_Neminatha%2C_and_Mahavira%29_LACMA_M.85.55_%281_of_4%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1682" data-file-height="2100" /></a></div><div class="thumbcaption"><i>Chaumukha</i> Sculpture with Four Jinas (Rishabhanatha (Adinatha), Parshvanatha, Neminatha, and Mahavira), <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LACMA" class="mw-redirect" title="LACMA">LACMA</a>, 6th century</div></div></div></div></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r923042769/mw-parser-output/.tmulti"/><div class="thumb tmulti tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:328px;max-width:328px"><div class="trow"><div class="tsingle" style="width:162px;max-width:162px"><div class="thumbimage"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Udayagiri_Caves_-_Rani_Gumpha_01.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Udayagiri_Caves_-_Rani_Gumpha_01.jpg/160px-Udayagiri_Caves_-_Rani_Gumpha_01.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="107" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Udayagiri_Caves_-_Rani_Gumpha_01.jpg/240px-Udayagiri_Caves_-_Rani_Gumpha_01.jpg 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Udayagiri_Caves_-_Rani_Gumpha_01.jpg/320px-Udayagiri_Caves_-_Rani_Gumpha_01.jpg 2x" data-file-width="5053" data-file-height="3368" /></a></div><div class="thumbcaption"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Udayagiri_and_Khandagiri_Caves" title="Udayagiri and Khandagiri Caves">Udayagiri and Khandagiri Caves</a> built by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/King_Kharavela" class="mw-redirect" title="King Kharavela">King Kharavela</a> of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahameghavahana_dynasty" title="Mahameghavahana dynasty">Mahameghavahana dynasty</a> in 2nd century BCE</div></div><div class="tsingle" style="width:162px;max-width:162px"><div class="thumbimage"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:La_grotte_Jain_Indra_Sabha_Ellora_Caves,_India.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/La_grotte_Jain_Indra_Sabha_Ellora_Caves%2C_India.jpg/160px-La_grotte_Jain_Indra_Sabha_Ellora_Caves%2C_India.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="109" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/La_grotte_Jain_Indra_Sabha_Ellora_Caves%2C_India.jpg/240px-La_grotte_Jain_Indra_Sabha_Ellora_Caves%2C_India.jpg 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/La_grotte_Jain_Indra_Sabha_Ellora_Caves%2C_India.jpg/320px-La_grotte_Jain_Indra_Sabha_Ellora_Caves%2C_India.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1754" data-file-height="1200" /></a></div><div class="thumbcaption">The Indra Sabha cave at the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellora_Caves" title="Ellora Caves">Ellora Caves</a>, are co-located with Hindu and Buddhist monuments.</div></div></div></div></div>
<p>Jainism is an ancient <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_religion" class="mw-redirect" title="Indian religion">Indian religion</a> of obscure origins.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESangave2001185_315-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTESangave2001185-315">&#91;305&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERankinMardia2013975_316-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTERankinMardia2013975-316">&#91;306&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192513_317-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192513-317">&#91;307&#93;</a></sup> Jains claim it to be eternal, and consider the first <i>tirthankara</i> <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rishabhanatha" title="Rishabhanatha">Rishabhanatha</a> as its earthly founder.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192516_318-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192516-318">&#91;308&#93;</a></sup> Scholars have conjectured without reliable evidence that images such as those of the bull in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indus_Valley_Civilization" class="mw-redirect" title="Indus Valley Civilization">Indus Valley Civilization</a> seal are related to Jainism.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTELong201353–54_319-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTELong201353–54-319">&#91;309&#93;</a></sup> It is one of the <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C5%9Arama%E1%B9%87a" title="Śramaṇa">Śramaṇa</a></i> traditions of ancient India, those that rejected the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Veda" class="mw-redirect" title="Veda">Vedas</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTELochtefeld2002639_320-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTELochtefeld2002639-320">&#91;310&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBillimoria19881–30_321-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBillimoria19881–30-321">&#91;311&#93;</a></sup> and according to the philosopher <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarvepalli_Radhakrishnan" title="Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan">Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan</a>, it existed before them.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEJambuvijaya2002114_322-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJambuvijaya2002114-322">&#91;312&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPande1957353_323-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPande1957353-323">&#91;313&#93;</a></sup> 
</p><p>According to historians, the first 22 <i>tirthankaras</i> were mythical.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESangave2001104,_129_324-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTESangave2001104,_129-324">&#91;314&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESaraswati1908444_325-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTESaraswati1908444-325">&#91;315&#93;</a></sup> The 23rd, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parshvanatha" title="Parshvanatha">Parshvanatha</a>, is based on a historic person,<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEZimmer1953183_326-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEZimmer1953183-326">&#91;316&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEJaini199810_327-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJaini199810-327">&#91;317&#93;</a></sup> possibly of the eighth to sixth century BCE.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBarnett19577_328-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBarnett19577-328">&#91;318&#93;</a></sup> Mahāvīra is considered a contemporary of the Buddha, in around the 5th century BCE.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDundas2003a383_329-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDundas2003a383-329">&#91;319&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKeownPrebish2013127–130_330-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKeownPrebish2013127–130-330">&#91;320&#93;</a></sup> The interaction between the two religions began with the Buddha;<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESangave2001105_331-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTESangave2001105-331">&#91;321&#93;</a></sup> later, they competed for followers and the merchant trade networks that sustained them.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHirakawa19934–7_252-1" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHirakawa19934–7-252">&#91;244&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENeelis201072–76_332-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTENeelis201072–76-332">&#91;322&#93;</a></sup> Buddhist and Jain texts sometimes have the same or similar titles but present different doctrines.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEQvarnström2003ix–xi,_151–162_333-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEQvarnström2003ix–xi,_151–162-333">&#91;323&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Jains consider the kings <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bimbisara" title="Bimbisara">Bimbisara</a> (c. 558–491 BCE), <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ajatashatru" title="Ajatashatru">Ajatashatru</a> (c. 492–460 BCE), and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Udayin" title="Udayin">Udayin</a> (c. 460–440 BCE) of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haryanka_dynasty" title="Haryanka dynasty">Haryanka dynasty</a> as patrons of Jainism.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192541_334-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192541-334">&#91;324&#93;</a></sup> Jain tradition states that <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chandragupta_Maurya" title="Chandragupta Maurya">Chandragupta Maurya</a> (322–298 BCE), the founder of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mauryan_Empire" class="mw-redirect" title="Mauryan Empire">Mauryan Empire</a> and grandfather of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ashoka" title="Ashoka">Ashoka</a>, became a monk and disciple of Jain ascetic <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhadrabahu" title="Bhadrabahu">Bhadrabahu</a> in the later part of his life.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKulkeRothermund200463–65_335-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKulkeRothermund200463–65-335">&#91;325&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBoesche20037–18_336-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBoesche20037–18-336">&#91;326&#93;</a></sup> Jain texts state that he died intentionally at Shravanabelagola by fasting.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMookerji198839–46,_234–236_337-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMookerji198839–46,_234–236-337">&#91;327&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKulkeRothermund200463–65_335-1" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKulkeRothermund200463–65-335">&#91;325&#93;</a></sup> Versions of Chandragupta's story appear in Buddhist, Jain, and Hindu texts.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMookerji19884–21,_232–237_338-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMookerji19884–21,_232–237-338">&#91;328&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192542_339-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192542-339">&#91;329&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The 3rd century BCE emperor Ashoka, in his pillar edicts, mentions the <i>Niganthas</i> (Jains).<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192543_340-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192543-340">&#91;330&#93;</a></sup> <i>Tirthankara</i> statues date back to the second century BC.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEUpinder_Singh2016444_341-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEUpinder_Singh2016444-341">&#91;331&#93;</a></sup> Archeological evidence suggests that Mathura was an important Jain center from the 2nd century BCE onwards.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEJainFischer19789–10_266-1" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJainFischer19789–10-266">&#91;257&#93;</a></sup> Inscriptions from as early as the 1st century CE already show the schism between Digambara and Śvētāmbara.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192549_342-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192549-342">&#91;332&#93;</a></sup> There is inscriptional evidence for the presence of Jain monks in south India by the second or first centuries BC, and archaeological evidence of Jain monks in Saurashtra in Gujarat by the second century CE.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTECort2010202_343-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTECort2010202-343">&#91;333&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Royal patronage has been a key factor in the growth and decline of Jainism.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENatubhai_Shah200469–70_344-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTENatubhai_Shah200469–70-344">&#91;334&#93;</a></sup> In the second half of the 1st century CE, Hindu kings of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rashtrakuta" class="mw-redirect" title="Rashtrakuta">Rashtrakuta</a> dynasty sponsored major Jain cave temples.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPereira197721–24_345-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPereira197721–24-345">&#91;335&#93;</a></sup> King <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harshavardhana" class="mw-redirect" title="Harshavardhana">Harshavardhana</a> of the 7th century championed Jainism, Buddhism and all traditions of Hinduism.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192552_346-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192552-346">&#91;336&#93;</a></sup> The Pallava King <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahendravarman_I" title="Mahendravarman I">Mahendravarman I</a> (600–630 CE) converted from Jainism to Shaivism.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTELochtefeld2002409_347-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTELochtefeld2002409-347">&#91;337&#93;</a></sup> His work <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mattavilasa_Prahasana" title="Mattavilasa Prahasana">Mattavilasa Prahasana</a></i> ridicules certain Shaiva sects and the Buddhists and expresses contempt for Jain ascetics.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEArunachalam1981170_348-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEArunachalam1981170-348">&#91;338&#93;</a></sup> The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seuna_(Yadava)_dynasty" title="Seuna (Yadava) dynasty">Yadava dynasty</a> built many temples at the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellora_Caves" title="Ellora Caves">Ellora Caves</a> between 700 and 1000 CE.<sup id="cite_ref-asiintro_349-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-asiintro-349">&#91;339&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGopal1990178_350-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGopal1990178-350">&#91;340&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEOwen2012b1–10_351-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEOwen2012b1–10-351">&#91;341&#93;</a></sup> King <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C4%80ma" title="Āma">Āma</a> of the 8th century converted to Jainism, and the Jain pilgrimage tradition was well established in his era.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192552–54_352-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192552–54-352">&#91;342&#93;</a></sup> <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mularaja" title="Mularaja">Mularaja</a> (10th century CE), the founder of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chalukya_dynasty" title="Chalukya dynasty">Chalukya dynasty</a>, constructed a Jain temple, even though he was not a Jain.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192556_353-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192556-353">&#91;343&#93;</a></sup> During the 11th century, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basava" title="Basava">Basava</a>, a minister to the Jain <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalachuris_of_Kalyani" title="Kalachuris of Kalyani">Kalachuri</a> king <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bijjala_II" title="Bijjala II">Bijjala</a>, converted many Jains to the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lingayatism" title="Lingayatism">Lingayat</a> Shaivite sect. The Lingayats destroyed Jain temples and adapted them to their use.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192575–77_354-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192575–77-354">&#91;344&#93;</a></sup> The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hoysala_Dynasty" class="mw-redirect" title="Hoysala Dynasty">Hoysala</a> King <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vishnuvardhana" title="Vishnuvardhana">Vishnuvardhana</a> (c. 1108–1152 CE) became a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vaishnava" class="mw-redirect" title="Vaishnava">Vaishnavite</a> under the influence of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ramanuja" title="Ramanuja">Ramanuja</a>, and Vaishnavism then grew rapidly in what is now Karnataka.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDas2005161_355-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDas2005161-355">&#91;345&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Medieval">Medieval</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Jainism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=31" title="Edit section: Medieval">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Gori_Mandar.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Jain monuments in Nagarparkar, Pakistan" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7c/Gori_Mandar.jpg/170px-Gori_Mandar.jpg" decoding="async" width="170" height="128" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7c/Gori_Mandar.jpg/255px-Gori_Mandar.jpg 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7c/Gori_Mandar.jpg/340px-Gori_Mandar.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3264" data-file-height="2448" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Gori_Mandar.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>The ruins of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Godiji#The_original_Gori_Temple_(گوری_مندر)_in_Tharparkar" title="Godiji">Gori Jain temples</a> in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nagarparkar" title="Nagarparkar">Nagarparkar</a>, Pakistan, a pilgrimage site before 1947.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_356-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-:0-356">&#91;346&#93;</a></sup></div></div></div>
<p>Jainism faced persecution during and after the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muslim_conquests_on_the_Indian_subcontinent" class="mw-redirect" title="Muslim conquests on the Indian subcontinent">Muslim conquests on the Indian subcontinent</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDundas2002145–146,_124_357-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDundas2002145–146,_124-357">&#91;347&#93;</a></sup> Muslims rulers, such as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahmud_Ghazni" class="mw-redirect" title="Mahmud Ghazni">Mahmud Ghazni</a> (1001), <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mohammad_Ghori" class="mw-redirect" title="Mohammad Ghori">Mohammad Ghori</a> (1175) and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alauddin_Khalji" title="Alauddin Khalji">Ala-ud-din Muhammed Shah Khalji</a> (1298) further oppressed the Jain community.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192574–75_358-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEvon_Glasenapp192574–75-358">&#91;348&#93;</a></sup> They vandalised idols and destroyed temples or converted them into mosques. They also burned Jain books and killed Jains. There were significant exceptions, such as Emperor <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akbar" title="Akbar">Akbar</a> (1542–1605) whose legendary religious tolerance, out of respect for Jains, ordered the release of caged birds and banned the killing of animals on the Jain festival of Paryusan.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDundas2002146_359-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDundas2002146-359">&#91;349&#93;</a></sup> After Akbar, Jains faced an intense period of Muslim persecution in the 17th century.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDundas2002220–221_360-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDundas2002220–221-360">&#91;350&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTETruschke20151311–1344_361-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTETruschke20151311–1344-361">&#91;351&#93;</a></sup> The Jain community were the traditional bankers and financiers, and this significantly impacted the Muslim rulers. However, they rarely were a part of the political power during the Islamic rule period of the Indian subcontinent.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTECort199885–86_362-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTECort199885–86-362">&#91;352&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Colonial_era">Colonial era</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Jainism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=32" title="Edit section: Colonial era">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Colonial era reports and Christian missions variously viewed Jainism as a sect of Hinduism, a sect of Buddhism, or a distinct religion.<sup id="cite_ref-363" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-363">&#91;353&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHopkins1902283_364-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHopkins1902283-364">&#91;354&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESunavala193491–93_365-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTESunavala193491–93-365">&#91;355&#93;</a></sup> Christian missionaries were frustrated at Jain people without pagan creator gods refusing to convert to Christianity, while colonial era Jain scholars such as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Champat_Rai_Jain" title="Champat Rai Jain">Champat Rai Jain</a> defended Jainism against criticism and misrepresentation by Christian activists.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEJaini200033_366-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJaini200033-366">&#91;356&#93;</a></sup> Missionaries of Christianity and Islam considered Jain traditions idolatrous and superstitious.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHackett200863–68_367-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHackett200863–68-367">&#91;357&#93;</a></sup> These criticisms, states <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_E._Cort" title="John E. Cort">John E. Cort</a>, were flawed and ignored similar practices within sects of Christianity.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTECort201012–16,_200–207,_218–219,_251_with_note_10_368-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTECort201012–16,_200–207,_218–219,_251_with_note_10-368">&#91;358&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The British colonial government in India and Indian princely states passed laws that made roaming naked an arrestable crime, particularly impacting Digambara monks.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFlügel2006348–349_369-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFlügel2006348–349-369">&#91;359&#93;</a></sup> The Akhil Bharatiya Jain Samaj opposed this law, arguing that it interfered with Jain religious rights. Acharya <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shantisagar" title="Shantisagar">Shantisagar</a> entered Bombay (now Mumbai) in 1927, but was forced to cover his body. He then led an India-wide tour as the naked monk with his followers, to various Digambara sacred sites, and was welcomed by kings of the Maharashtra provinces.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFlügel2006348–349_369-1" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFlügel2006348–349-369">&#91;359&#93;</a></sup> Shantisagar fasted to oppose the restrictions imposed on Digambara monks by the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_Raj" title="British Raj">British Raj</a> and prompted their discontinuance.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENatubhai_Shah200456_370-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTENatubhai_Shah200456-370">&#91;360&#93;</a></sup> The laws were abolished by India after independence.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFlügel2006359–360_371-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFlügel2006359–360-371">&#91;361&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Modern_era">Modern era</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Jainism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=33" title="Edit section: Modern era">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jain_community" class="mw-redirect" title="Jain community">Jain community</a></div>
<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acharya_Chandana" title="Acharya Chandana">Chandanaji</a> became the first Jain woman to receive the title of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acharya" title="Acharya">Acharya</a> in 1987.<sup id="cite_ref-MillerLong2019_372-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-MillerLong2019-372">&#91;362&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Followers of Jainism are called "Jains", a word derived from the Sanskrit <i>jina</i> (victor), which means an omniscient person who teaches the path of salvation.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESangave200615_373-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTESangave200615-373">&#91;363&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEUpinder_Singh2016313_35-1" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEUpinder_Singh2016313-35">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup> The majority of Jains currently reside in India. With four to five million followers worldwide,<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVoorst201496_374-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVoorst201496-374">&#91;364&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMeltonBaumann2010lix,_1395_375-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMeltonBaumann2010lix,_1395-375">&#91;365&#93;</a></sup> Jainism is small compared to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Major_religious_groups" title="Major religious groups">major world religions</a>. Jains form 0.37% of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jainism_in_India" title="Jainism in India">India</a>'s population, mostly in the states of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jainism_in_Maharashtra" title="Jainism in Maharashtra">Maharashtra</a> (1.4 million in 2011,<sup id="cite_ref-jaindemographics_376-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-jaindemographics-376">&#91;366&#93;</a></sup> 31.46% of Indian Jains), <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jainism_in_Rajasthan" title="Jainism in Rajasthan">Rajasthan</a> (13.97%), <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jainism_in_Gujarat" title="Jainism in Gujarat">Gujarat</a> (13.02%) and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madhya_Pradesh" title="Madhya Pradesh">Madhya Pradesh</a> (12.74%). <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jainism_in_Karnataka" title="Jainism in Karnataka">Karnataka</a> (9.89%), <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jainism_in_Uttar_Pradesh" title="Jainism in Uttar Pradesh">Uttar Pradesh</a> (4.79%), <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jainism_in_Delhi" title="Jainism in Delhi">Delhi</a> (3.73%) and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tamil_Jain" title="Tamil Jain">Tamil Nadu</a> (2.01%) also have significant Jain populations.<sup id="cite_ref-jaindemographics_376-1" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-jaindemographics-376">&#91;366&#93;</a></sup> Outside India, Jain communities can be found in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jainism_in_Europe" title="Jainism in Europe">Europe</a>, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jainism_in_the_United_Kingdom" title="Jainism in the United Kingdom">United Kingdom</a>, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jainism_in_the_United_States" title="Jainism in the United States">United States</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jainism_in_Canada" title="Jainism in Canada">Canada</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWiley200943_377-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWiley200943-377">&#91;367&#93;</a></sup> <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">Australia</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jainism_in_Africa" title="Jainism in Africa">Kenya</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMugambi2010108_378-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMugambi2010108-378">&#91;368&#93;</a></sup> Jainism is also spreading rapidly in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jainism_in_Japan" title="Jainism in Japan">Japan</a>, where there are more than 5,000 families who have converted to Jainism.<sup id="cite_ref-379" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-379">&#91;369&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>According to the National Family and Health Survey (NFHS-4) conducted in 2015–16, Jains form the wealthiest community in India.<sup id="cite_ref-380" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-380">&#91;370&#93;</a></sup> Jains have the highest literacy rate (87%) in India, in the 7-years to oldest age group, according to its 2011 census, and the most college graduates.<sup id="cite_ref-381" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-381">&#91;371&#93;</a></sup> Excluding the retired, Jain literacy in India exceeded 97%. The female to male child sex ratio in the 0–6 year age was second lowest for Jains (870 girls per 1,000 boys), higher than <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sikhism" title="Sikhism">Sikhs</a> in India. Jain males have the highest work participation rates in India, while Jain females have the lowest.<sup id="cite_ref-382" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-382">&#91;372&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Jainism has been praised for some of its practices and beliefs. The leader of the campaign for Indian independence, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahatma_Gandhi" title="Mahatma Gandhi">Mahatma Gandhi</a>, greatly influenced by Jainism, said:<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERudolphRudolph1984171_383-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTERudolphRudolph1984171-383">&#91;373&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r960796168">.mw-parser-output .templatequote{overflow:hidden;margin:1em 0;padding:0 40px}.mw-parser-output .templatequote .templatequotecite{line-height:1.5em;text-align:left;padding-left:1.6em;margin-top:0}</style><blockquote class="templatequote"><p>No religion in the World has explained the principle of <i>Ahiṃsā</i> so deeply and systematically as is discussed with its applicability in every human life in Jainism. As and when the benevolent principle of <i>Ahiṃsā</i> or non-violence will be ascribed for practice by the people of the world to achieve their end of life in this world and beyond, Jainism is sure to have the uppermost status and Mahāvīra is sure to be respected as the greatest authority on <i>Ahiṃsā</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEJanardan_Pandey199850_384-0" class="reference"><a href="Jainism#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJanardan_Pandey199850-384">&#91;374&#93;</a></sup></p></blockquote>
